04259nam a22006375i 9780292794221DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927942217 a10.7560/7180292doi  a(DE-B1597)587050  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aML3531bM34 2008 7aMUS0310002bisacsh04a782.4216491 aMcFarland, Pancho, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChicano Rap :bGender and Violence in the Postindustrial Barrio /cPancho McFarland. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: A Hip-Hop Project -- tChapter One. Reading Chicano Rap: The Patriarchal Dominance Paradigm in the Postindustrial Barrio -- tChapter Two. Chicano Rap Primer: A Guide to Artists and Genres -- tChapter Three. Machos y Malas Mujeres: The Gendered Image -- tChapter Four. Sexual Agency in Chicana Rap: JV Versus Ms. Sancha -- tChapter Five. Violence in Chicano Rap: Mirror of a Belligerent Society -- tChapter Six. The Chicano Rap on Globalization -- tChapter Seven. Confronting Dominance and Constructing Relationships with Youth -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPowered by a driving beat, clever lyrics, and assertive attitudes, rap music and hip hop culture have engrossed American youth since the mid-1980s. Although the first rappers were African Americans, rap and hip hop culture quickly spread to other ethnic groups who have added their own cultural elements to the music. Chicano Rap offers the first in-depth look at how Chicano/a youth have adopted and adapted rap music and hip hop culture to express their views on gender and violence, as well as on how Chicano/a youth fit into a globalizing world. Pancho McFarland examines over five hundred songs and seventy rap artists from all the major Chicano rap regions—San Diego, San Francisco and Northern California, Texas, and Chicago and the Midwest. He discusses the cultural, political, historical, and economic contexts in which Chicano rap has emerged and how these have shaped the violence and misogyny often expressed in Chicano rap and hip hop. In particular, he argues that the misogyny and violence of Chicano rap are direct outcomes of the "patriarchal dominance paradigm" that governs human relations in the United States. McFarland also explains how globalization, economic restructuring, and the conservative shift in national politics have affected Chicano/a youth and Chicano rap. He concludes with a look at how Xicana feminists, some Chicano rappers, and other cultural workers are striving to reach Chicano/a youth with a democratic, peaceful, empowering, and liberating message.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aMexican AmericansvMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aRap (Music)xHistory and criticism. 0aSex in music. 0aViolence in music. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Rap & Hip Hop.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794221423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794221/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK